\subtree{
\title{Data Updates and Versioning}
\p{The Open Targets Platform is updated \strong{quarterly} with new data releases. The current release (as of October 2025) is available at the API endpoint.}

\p{\strong{Release information:} Check https://platform-docs.opentargets.org/release-notes for the latest updates.}

\p{\strong{Citation:} When using Open Targets data, cite: Ochoa, D. et al. (2025) Open Targets Platform: facilitating therapeutic hypotheses building in drug discovery. Nucleic Acids Research, 53(D1):D1467-D1477.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Limitations and Considerations}
\ol{
\li{\strong{API is for exploratory queries:} For systematic analyses of many targets/diseases, use data downloads or BigQuery}
\li{\strong{Scores are relative, not absolute:} Association scores rank evidence strength but don't predict clinical success}
\li{\strong{Under-studied diseases score lower:} Novel or rare diseases may have strong evidence but lower aggregate scores}
\li{\strong{Evidence quality varies:} Weight expert-curated sources higher than computational predictions}
\li{\strong{Requires biological interpretation:} Scores and evidence must be interpreted in biological and clinical context}
\li{\strong{No authentication required:} All data is freely accessible, but cite appropriately}
}
}
}